rComments: Prof Cowan has the class set up for your success as long as you do the work. The readings are very heavy (80-100 pages a week) and the lectures are also full of information. The TAs are also pretty great and marking is pretty chill, but unless you're really into history, I wouldn't recommend. It's a lot of work.
Amazing prof. Shes kind and funny and respectable. However the readings are really heavy and shes a fast talker so keep up.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Dr. Cowan is a very knowledgeable and passionate prof. Her HIS101 class really helps prepare first-year students for university as she has you do a thesis assignment, annotated bibliography, essay, and essay revision. Her lecture slides are vague and don't contain much info so you should take thorough notes in class. She talks a bit fast as well.

She's a great history prof if you're interested in learning material history as well as contextual "textbook" events. The person who said they learned more about cleaning than history must have only come to the ONE lecture we spoke about that. If you want facts and dates, read a textbook. She makes history classes engaging and more relatable.
teacherRatingTags: ['EXTRA CREDIT', 'Tough grader', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: She kinda doesn't teach anything, its minor things you learn about and never get into specifics if you wanna learn history don't take this class. I spent more time learning about how a Dutch Mother cleans the house than actual history, she glossed over huge events in favor of playing music from the time period or other dumb stuff.

Best history prof I've had at utm. She has unbiased lectures that are clear and concise. I try to take all her classes. She also like giving bonus assignments for participation marks which is really great.

Mairi Cowan is one of the best professors I've ever had. She covers a lot in her lectures with minimal information on her powerpoints so it's definitely useful to come to class and take detailed notes. She doesn't really use the textbooks but she assigns several secondary readings each week that you need to know inside out for the exam.
Dr. Cowan had presented lectures which told stories and inspired us students to proceed in world history deep into our future. This course was the beginning of my double major at UTM.

Professor Cowan is one of the best professors I have had so far ! She is very kind and approachable. Her lectures are really interesting and she really wants her students to succeed. She is very fair. The exam is super easy ( as long as you study) and the essays are super helpful for learning the writing expected of you in university.

I hadn't taken history since 10th grade so I had low expectations. I ended up loving the class. The course material was interesting, Blackboard weekly quizzes were easy marks as were in-class clicker questions. There were two essays that were very clear - you get a second chance to fix the first essay if you messed up. The exam was very fair.
teacherRatingTags: ['Clear grading criteria', 'Get ready to read', 'Participation matters']

rComments: Her lectures are very interesting but readings are too much! She is very passionate about the subject and sort of expects us to think like Historians. Tutorial readings were heavy and exam was difficult because she expects her students to know a lot.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: Professor Cowan is a great lecturer who has a diverse knowledge of European history. She gives dense readings which take time to read but it helps you better understand the class. If you pay attention and try to do the readings, you'll definitely get a 70+. She's a little intimidating at first but she's a pleasure to have as a professor.
teacherRatingTags: ['Amazing lectures', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Tough grader']

rComments: She's a great speaker and makes classes interesting. LOTS of textbook reading and weekly online quizzes (but they really help). Uses iClicker in lectures, which makes it more fun. You should actually be interested. My only critique is that the assignments aren't really related to the course material.
teacherRatingTags: ['Participation matters', 'Get ready to read', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: She may act casual, but she treats her students and coursework in a professional and attentive way. She is easy to approach, and truly enjoys what she teaches. She replies emails at lightning speed. She expects hard work and lots of reading. She tries to help students gain fuller experience through external sources. One very dedicated professor.

Pretty good prof, expects a lot out of students which sometimes meant having us read a little bit too much (100 pages per week!) for one course. Very helpful and approachable however, fair grader and fair tests. Felt like she maybe tried too do too much with developing writing styles when it would be better to deal with course content.
teacherRatingTags: ['Respected', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: She seems like a really nice prof, but she marks kind of hard. Her TA for his230 is absolutely awful, probably the worst TA i have ever had in all of university. No point for a tutorial for his230 so dont understand why there is one. Boring class, although the prof is so into the material. Wouldn't recommend this course.

Dr. Cowan is an angel! She always shows that she wants the class to do their best and is very kind to every student. Her grading criteria is very clear and fair. Personally, I also found her to be very inspirational as a teacher and person. Despite the fact that I disliked this course, Dr. Cowan made my time spent there worthwhile.
She is an outstanding prof! Highly recommend taking this class!

She is one of the best profs I've had.  She makes the topics interesting and always brings in primary sources into her lectures through songs, videos of plays, and pictures.  She really cares about her students and if you go talk to her about the paper topic she will direct you where to look for sources, and how to refine the thesis.
Really helpful and she shows she cares!
Good prof. makes the lectures enjoyable and learnt a lot in her course. Doesnt have many testes which are nice just a couple of writing piece and makes it engaging with using the iclicker.
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: Very nice,  very enjoyable course, learnt lots. I am somewhat a history buff and learnt lots from this prof.
Great lecturer. Really makes History interesting when the students are willing to listen and participate in tutorials. Simple essays to write and will aid students who have questions. Great prof!

Dr. Cowan makes history come to life in her lectures. She tells history like a story and can make even the most boring topics seem interesting. She is also very kind and willing to help you if you have any problems. Her passion for history shows when she is teaching and also spreads to her students. Hands down one of my favourite professors at UTM.

I find it very neat that she uses Online Quizzes  (worth 10% of overall grades) to help our understanding of the material. That, combined with the i-clickers (5%) are basically free 15% of the marks. The tutorials are a problem since participation is worth 20% which I believe is too much.  Lecture notes are essential for the finals. No term tests.
Can be a bit pretentious at times, but overall, she's a great lecturer.

Professor Cowan was easily one of my favourite professors at UofT I loved the lectures her presentations were clear and concise and being a history buff myself I learned a lot more and was motivated to learn I loved how her tone of voice noted appropriate humor in lecture. And of course she is easily one of the most attractive professors there.

I took two classes with her, I found in the 100 level she was not a good professor at all, maybe because it was a large class or first years but she treated everyone like kids. In my 400 level class, with only about 20 people in it, she was much more helpful, attentive, and nicer overall. Also my 4th year class was related more to her field.

Her syllabus isn't accurate. She said to study the quizzes in preparation for the final exam but when I took the course 90% of the questions were from the lecture. If I had known this I could have gotten a higher grade.

Took this class last year when it was offered. She did have interesting lectures, but sometimes they dragged on a bit. Marking depends on your TA as she doesn't mark any of the essays or anything. Tutorial readings could be a little daunting, especially with 30 pages in small font on convictions in the 1600s. Overall not bad.
I took two classes with her, i found I didn't like her in the first class, but later I realized that it was just the topic I didn't like, she is a great person even though she teaches boring classes.
I hated this course. And she focuses on food so much. Worst course and prof ever

Hands down prof cowan made me love history. She is so enthusiastic about the material that you can't help but be encouraged as well! However, she never post lecture slides online so attendance is MORE THAN IMPORTANT and I cant emphasize this point enough.

She is a clear and engaging speaker. She does not attempt to confuse her students whatsoever which is what I liked about her. She made a horrible topic into a relatively LESS boring topic - still boring. For a first year course, it is unreasonably difficult. If you can, take the first year HIS102 course downtown. More interesting!

Not a bad professor, but the only thing is she and her T.A wrote journal articles together and so she would talk highly of the T.A. The problem with that it is difficult to approach a Professor about a horrible T.A when they have a strong affiliation together.
BEST PROF EVER. She's so enthusiastic about her work. I had her for HIS101 as well; easy high 70-80 in her classes. She's very helpful and cheerful. I must take more history courses with her.
Really nice and helpful proff. keeps the content interesting and tries to make the course easy for first years

Very easy to follow and is excited to teach history. The content for this term is boring (the history of food) but the reality of her his101 course is that she is preparing students to seek important unfamiliar information, analyze its content and to place their ideas on paper. Highly recommended to new university students.
easy to follow in lecture and easy to understand. Overall this is whats profs should be like.

She's nice enough but the class material is awful. The History of FOOD!?! As a history 101 Subject guideline!?! Terrible, very boring all you talk about is Bachus and tea. Do not take HIST101 with her. Plus the incorporated essay guide is so useless. How do you write an essay? Very obvious painful to listen to information is shared each class.

Great Prof! Really smart and cares about students. Course is designed with a lot of weekly commitment. If you keep up with weekly quizzes/readings and show up to class you will do well. Great speaking skills.

Certainly qualified for her profession. She shows a very keen interest in her work and is clearly highly intelligent. Her courses are great for history buffs and nerds and also fantastic for exposing laziness in a great number of pupils - as her courses demand a very high quantity of reading and close detailed work. She certainly prepares one well!

Interesting professor, but uses tricking lecturing strategies to convey important information. She gives important information very indirectly. Never stutters, very clear and projects her voice well. Always had a smile on her face when visited her.
Really enthusiastic about the course - especially facts regarding music and religion. If you make time to do the readings, you'll do just great :)
great Prof in the 101 course she looks another (more boring less bearable) person in this one she is totally commited to her job, and makes it much more interesting

She is a decent prof, but the way she structured this course is terrible. The course changes every year and this year its covering the history of food from the 1600's which is such a dry topic. Best way to survive this course, is find a way to make the readings not so boring. At the end of the day, this course needs to be better organized.
Enthusiastic.  Helpful when you ask for help.  If you work hard, her class is worth is.
Has no idea what she's doing. Most disorganized class ever.
